= Proof by contradiction

Let us more carefully examine the argument in #emph[Capital] to observe how it forecloses modern freedom through the movement of its forms.
Marx's method comprises what I will call (and elaborate in future chapters) a #strong[critique of calculus].
His critique pertains not only to the capitalist calculus of value with reference to labor, I argue, but also to the ontological sensibility of how modern calculus as a method locates truth more generally.
This critique reveals a commitment to the ontological importance of #emph[contradiction] in the appearance of truth.
In recognizing that Marx's philosophical standpoint sits squarely #emph[in] history rather than outside of it, Postone identifies the method of #emph[Capital] as an #strong[immanent critique] of economic rationality.
It starts from and stays within the conceptual world of economic axioms, and proceeds by revealing the sites of logical contradiction in its discursive edifice.

In Volume I, Marx argues that capital reproduces itself without any apparent need for human labor, despite the labor-power of the worker's transformation into variable capital being absolutely essential to the manufacture of surplus-value (an argument laid out in chapter
21).
#footnote[All chapter number references in this chapter, unless otherwise stated, refer to the 2024 English translation of Volume I @marxCapitalCritiquePolitical2024.]
Capital appears to produce value as if it were a machine, driven by some motive force that is not necessarily human labor, such as steam or horse-power.
But this appearance contradicts the logical form of value as it is chiefly unfolded with reference to money, labor-time, and surplus value in chapters 1 through 6, as this logic holds that surplus-value can only be expropriated from a particular kind of of commodity, namely labor-power.
The constitutive distortion between human and machine at stake in this self-valorizing appearance of capital is produced by a series of successive contradictory concepts, each one unfolding from the contradiction located in the last.
#footnote[This unfolding is sometimes referred to as Marx's dialectical method.
I avoid this terminology here because, as Michael Heinrich notes in his introduction to #emph[Capital], the 'dialectical' qualification has historically been used as much to mystify Marx's deep commitment to logic, rationality and contradiction as it has to clarify it @heinrichIntroductionThreeVolumes2012[ pp.36-38].
My positioning of Marx's method in #emph[Capital] as a prototype of a critique of calculus can, however, be understood as an attempt to disentangle what is mathematically at stake in dialectics as a modus operandi in philosophy.]

Let us begin, then, where Marx does in chapter 1, with the concept of the commodity {#emph[die Waare]}.
We will notate the commodity as $C$ and take it to mean, following Marx, a good that is conceptually exchangeable for another good.
There is nothing distinctly physical about a commodity: it is #quote[an external object {#emph[ein 채usserer Gegenstand]}-- a thing whose properties satisfy human wants or needs {#emph[menschliche Bed체rfnisse]} of whatever kind {#emph[irgend einer Art]}] @marxCapitalCritiquePolitical2024[p.13].
The German term for object used here, #emph[Gegenstand], refers in the vocabulary of German idealism (a core component of Marx's philosophical education) to something that 'stands against' {#emph[Gegen]-#emph[stand];} the perceiving subject, i.e. an object as it appears to consciousness.
#footnote[Marx's qualified use of the term #emph[Gegenstandlichkeit] in #emph[Capital] to describe the spectral thingliness of the commodity is often translated into English as simply 'objectivity'.
This translation obscures the nuance of the term, which is best thought about with the decomposition of the base term #emph[Gegenstand] in mind, i.e. as 'standing-against-(the-subject)-liness' or perhaps as 'objectified-liness'.
Frank Engster provides a concise explanation of the nuance of this term's implications in Marx's philosophical context in @foreignobjektFrankEngsterBlind2021[ 24:28-25:00].]
The adjective #emph[채usserer] is translated as external, as it refers in the same philosophical tradition to a space outside of the perceiving subject, rather than an internal abstraction that is private to the perceiver's personal mind.
Thus the commodity is an object-impression perceived by an observer that is not just a private hallucination, but rather is a #emph[shared] concept, and thus has the sense of being external.

The commodity is not limited to objects in the colloquial sense, as it is a notion that can apply, as Marx specifies in the quotation above, to anything that satisfies a need or desire of any kind.
A service, therefore, can be a commodity, as can something visually invisible but sensible in some other way, such as a smell or a sound, as can apparently 'immaterial' things such as software.
What commodifies an object in the terms of Marx's argument is its thinkability as exchangeable, its acquisition of exchange-value, its expression or #emph[naming] as a representative quantity in the circuit of social value.
A software company that sells a subscription service is producing commodities at this conceptual level just as much as an steel factory that is processing iron and carbon in a furnace.
Commodity production does not refer exclusively to the more palpably material processes that we associate with the industrial revolution, but to giving of quantities to objects that are then taken to express their value:

#lemma[
The commodity is the name of the moment in which an object is made conceptually exchangeable by means of a quantity that is taken to express its social value.
] <lem:commodity>

The misunderstanding of a commodity as exclusively a physical product that can change hands gives rise to other misunderstandings, such as the idea that capital no longer structures daily life in our present conditions of exchange.
Jodi Dean has recently put forward, for example, building on prior arguments from Mackenzie Wark and Yanis Varoufakis, that capital is dying and threatens to be replaced by a new-- and even more life-threatening-- paradigm of sociality that could be called 'neofeudalism' @deanCapitalsGraveNeofeudalism2025@warkCapitalDeadThis2021@varoufakisTechnofeudalismWhatKilled2024. The evidence of capital's moribund state, according to Dean, is the preponderance of services such as those provided by Uber drivers, which are taken to represent a form of exchange that is no longer the commodity.
As explained above, however, services such as Uber rides and those in the so-called can be treated as commodities just as much as tangibly graspable products such as steel bars and paper clips.
Thus to say that the salience of Uber as a major player in the economy is evidence of the decline of commodification is to misunderstand the generality of the commodity concept as Marx presents it; i.e. as any 'thing' that is thinkable as quantifiably exchangeable.
If the commodity and the capital-logic that follows from it are on their deathbeds, as Marx theorized them, it cannot be on sole account of a booming service economy: for services can be commodities, too, when their value is expressed in a given quantity such as a dollar amount.

There is nothing inherently un-commodity-like, then, about either services or software as such.
The consequences of this point regarding how Marx helps us to understand the structure of 'information society' will be explored in later chapters, but let us return now to the commodity's conceptual unfolding at its most elementary.
The commodity is any object that is rendered in thought as a #emph[quantity] (as possessing an exchange-value).
There are objects in the world that we use in our day-to-day lives; but if there is no way to imagine that object of thought as exchangeable with some other thought-object, then it is not a commodity in the sense in which Marx is interested in that term.
It is the commodity concept's inherent exchangeability that Marx logically develops into a notion of value.
Value is the consistency through which it becomes possible to think one commodity as exchangeable for another, the (subjective) quality of a thing that recognizes it may satisfy a person's want, need, or desire.
In order for commodity exchange to be sensible, value must take a material form in the world, which is precisely what gives rise to money {#emph[das Geld]}, which we will notate as $M$.
#footnote[Note that I have translated the original German symbols $W$ {#emph[Waare]} and $G$ {#emph[Geld]} into $C$ (commodity) and $M$ (money) for the convenience of the English reader, following the standard convention.]
Money is the objective measure of the value in commodity exchange.
The process of exchange that constitutes capital is thus often notated as $M arrow.r C arrow.r M'$, a process that we will unpack in more detail shortly.
The $'$ in this formula can be pronounced 'prime', and it indicates the surplus-value that accrues to the capitalist after his money has been valorized in its circulation as a commodity.
Exchange in the mode of production called capital is the ongoing transformation of these two concepts, the commodity and money, into each other.
A commodity is exchanged for money, so that that money can be exchanged for (other) commodities.

Each of these concepts, money and the commodity, logically implies the other.
There can be no money, which emerges as a quantitative measure of value in the commodity, without the commodity.
Vice versa, without the complementary concept of money, the commodity would be incomplete as a concept.
Commodities would have no quantified measure of value, and so would have to individually be thought as exchangeable for a concrete set of things, rather than as exchangeable for the infinite set of all commodities-- the set of anything that can be valued as exchangeable.
In this way, money is an idea that is complementary and necessary to the commodity's coherence as a concept.
Without money, the commodity would not be a commodity at all.
#footnote[The complementarity of the commodity and money concepts is why, despite Althusser's infamous objection to the decision, Marx opens #emph[Capital] with the notoriously difficult chapters on the commodity (chapter 1), exchange (chapter 2), and money (chapter 3).
The circuit of exchange and its dual polarities ($C$ and $M$) are the logical kernel of capital, which is to say that they #emph[are] the bases of how capital appears to us in thought.]

We can specify the complementarity of the commodity and money as concepts by showing how the latter logically emerges from the former.
The commodity $C$ consists, as argued above, in the quality of its universal exchangeability.
A given commodity $A$ is conceptually exchangeable for any other commodity $B$ in the set of all commodities.
#footnote[This notation of two commodities as $A$ and $B$ follows Marx's original (German) notation.
Other notational decisions in this section also follow Marx where not otherwise specified.]
The commodity $A$ here should be recognized as abstract in the same sense as $B$, in that it is not just one particular commodity that is exchangeable, but #emph[any] commodity sampled from the set of all commodities.
More generally put, any commodity $A$ is exchangeable for any other commodity $B$:

