  [$A arrow.r B$],
  caption: [Commodity exchangeability (basic form)],
) <commodity:basic>

In order for this exchange to make logical sense, we can recognize that there must be something 'in' $A$ that is also 'in' $B$.
Marx calls this shared quality of commodities $A$ and $B$ #emph[exchange-value].
Exchange-value is not some tangible or physical quality that consists in both of the things that $A$ and $B$ index, but rather a quality that emerges #emph[by virtue of $A$ and $B$ becoming thought as commodities].
Exchange-value is a quality given by thought, by the thinkability of two things as exchangeable, rather than something that exists in the thing itself.

Recall that, as Marx is working from the axioms of political economy, we assume that all exchanges of commodities are 'fair'.
The exchange is made fair by equalizing the exchange-value of $A$ and $B$.
This equalization precipitates the appearance of a #emph[quantity] that works in tandem with exchange-value as a quality.
Marx's famous explanatory example here is that 20 yards of linen might be exchanged for 1 coat @marxCapitalCritiquePolitical2024[p.39].
The exponents '20' and '1' operate as the equalizing quantities, commensurating the exchange-value quality that is thought to exist in both linen and the coat.
We can call the quantities required to equalize the exchange-value of $A$ and $B$ for the sake of apparent fairness $x$ and $y$ respectively, expanding the basic form of commodity equation into the following simple-relative {#emph[einfache relative];} form:

#figure(
  [$x A arrow.r y B$],
  caption: [Commodity exchangeability (simple-relative form)],
) <commodity:simplerelative>


The quantites $x$ and $y$ liquidate the commodities $A$ and $B$ as fairly exchangeable in thought by the equalization of their exchange-value.
But how exactly are $A$ and $B$ made exchangeable in practice?
The answer, as Marx notes in chapter 3, is through their measurement in a singularly consistent 'third' commodity, which we already know to be $M$: money.
Money is the operative concept through which commodities become #emph[practically] exchangeable, the material anchor of their conceptual equalization.
We might say that money gives weight to the concept of the commodity as a universally exchangeable thing; which is to say that money gives weight to the concept of the commodity as such.

Marx begins #emph[Capital] with an elaboration of the commodity's wily concept because it is the elementary unit of capital's edifice as a set of inherently dependent ideas, the axiomatic 'brick' of its logical architecture.
The commodity necessitates a notion of money; as to act on its notion there needs to exist an exceptional commodity that guarantees the consistency of the commodity's universal exchangeability.
Money sutures the open wound of the commodity's impossible universality, providing a tangible way to act on the unthinkable infinity of #emph[all] possible commodity exchanges.

The two terms $M$ and $C$ are thus the denotative basis for Marx's logical unfolding of capital's consequences in the remainder of #emph[Capital], which is to say that they are the unit vectors of the geometry of capital as a totality {#emph[Totalit채t]}.
#footnote[As Lukacs notes, it is part and parcel of Marx's dialectical method to begin from the atomistic, apparently simple slices of society's conceptualization: #quote[Only in this context which sees the isolated facts of social life as aspects of the historical process and integrates them in a totality, can knowledge of the facts hope to become knowledge of reality. This knowledge starts from the simple (and to the capitalist world), pure, immediate, natural determinants described above. It progresses from them to the knowledge of the concrete totality, i.e. to the conceptual reproduction of reality. This concrete totality is by no means an unmediated datum for thought.] @lukacsHistoryClassConsciousness1972[p.8]]
The apparently pure and immediate categories $C$ and $M$ are not 'natural', as the economists would have it.
They are not self-sufficient and given, but rather logically depend on each other like the axes in a Cartesian coordinate system.
This is no flippant mathematical reference.
The commodity and money are the axiomatic bases of capital as a logical system as it is constructed on the premise of fair exchange.

Marx's critique of capital as a system of free and fair relations between people shares something critical with the mathematical method of proof by contradiction, in that it shows that the commodity's elementary pretext of fair exchange cannot logically amount, when expanded, to a system in which all become systematically better off.
