As a mathematical method, proof by contradiction starts with an already-proven statement $S$.
One then proceeds to draw consequences from the contrary statement, not $S$ ($-S$), and works to reveal that at some point in the logical unfolding, a contradiction of an already-proven statement occurs.
When such a violation of a known fact appears, it can be safely assumed that the statement $-S$ is untenable, and therefore the opposite $S$ must be true.

Marx's immanent critique of the capital relation as a structure works by way of a similar principle.
If capital is logically consistent as a system, then its founding principle in the commodity as a universally exchangeable element should not violate the idea that the kinds of exchange that logically unfolds from it remains free and fair.
What Marx's analysis seeks to show is that capital is not, as the economic consensus claims, a mode of production uniquely suited to universal freedom and prosperity.
It is conversely a set of logically inconsistent conjectures that cannot stand up to the scrutiny of thorough rational examination.
#footnote[In a private letter, Marx made the imperious claim that the first volume of #emph[Capital] #quote[is without question the most terrible missile {#emph[furchtbarste Missile]} that has yet been hurled at the heads of the bourgeoisie] @marxMarxEngelsCorrespondence18671867.
  When we understand #emph[Capital] as a repudiation of the classical economic conception of society in its own terms, as a revelation of the contradiction at the heart of its logic, this claim does perhaps not seem so far off its mark.]
We will see later in this chapter how Marx's observance of contradictory nature of capital's concepts bears a reference to Russell's paradox and the emergence of set theory, not yet historically realized in Marx's own time given his death in 1883.
Indeed, it is the status of contradiction as a mathematical consistency in Marx's critical method that will allow us to see #emph[Capital] as the groundwork {#emph[Grundrisse]} for the sketch of the sexuated subject in the famous Lacanian formulas later in this chapter, and which will subsequently serve as the foundation for my case that Marxian critique remains material in our computationally inflected present.

Just as the commodity cannot be separated from money, supply cannot be separated from demand; production cannot be separated from circulation; and the capitalist cannot be separated from the proletariat (as we will see in the next section).
Each term can only ever be reasonably defined as the opposite of its other, as one pole of a concept in motion towards its opposite.
#footnote[This argument is made in David Harvey's introduction to #emph[Capital] @harveyCompanionMarxsCapital2018 as well as a more recent article in the New Left Review titled #emph[Value in Motion] @harveyValueMotion2020.]
Capital's totality is an economy of terms that, while in the realm of appearances {#emph[Erscheinung]} can seem self-sufficient and independent, in actuality {#emph[Sittlichkeit]} produces meaning only in the terms' relations to each other.
Capital's forms of appearance are not pure concepts that can be taken at face value, but are #quote[phenomena that conceal the inner working of [capital accumulation's] mechanism] @marxCapitalCritiquePolitical2024[p.520].
This split between appearance and reality is revealed, as we have seen, through the contradiction in capital's logical forms.
Capital-logic's claim that it is consistent is shown to be false, for there are immanent inconsistencies, internal flaws that cannot be ironed out through reform within the system, in its working.
Consequences emerge from these inconsistencies that are logically unaccountable in capital's conscious thought, its appearance.

We will call the realm of unaccountable consequences that necessarily emerges as the shadowy underside of capital-logic #strong[the unconscious].
As with the mathematical terminology above, this psychoanalytic lexicon is not spurious.
Psychoanalysis and the critique of political economy share in the recognition that reality cannot, logically speaking, consist simply of what appears to be the case.
The methods share a mutual and material mistrust in the consistency of thought.
#footnote[The philosopher Paul Ricouer thus nominates Marx and Freud as two, along with Nietzsche, 'masters of suspicion' in the canon of modern philosophy.]
Leopoldina Fortunati, one of Marx's most astute feminist readers in the late nineteenth century, refers to the unconscious that capital indexes as the sphere of #emph[reproduction] to evocatively counterpoint value's home stomping-grounds in the sphere of production @fortunatiLarcanoRiproduzioneCasalinghe1981.
#footnote[For the best English translation of Fortunati's book, refer to @fortunatiArcanaReproductionHousewives2025.]
Reproduction is the domain of activities that are not consciously counted in capital's calculus and as such cannot appear to matter (have value) in the context of its logic, such as the unpaid and thus 'unproductive' feminine labor that constitutes housework (cleaning, cooking, caring) and the biologically reproductive labor of carrying a child and giving birth.
That capital renders these kinds of labor unproductive with respect to its objective measure of value in money is striking evidence that something duplicitous lurks beneath the express idea that individuals are paid fairly according to their societal worth. Feminine reproductive labor is surely worth a significant #emph[something] when it comes to organizing a society in which human life is flourishing, one would have thought!
Yet capital-logic cannot account for it according to its conscious conception of value.

Marx's argument in #emph[Capital] is thus that capital is a #emph[synthetic] totality, not an actual one.
Though it is self-consciously totalizing-- that is, it appears to itself to be fully accountable-- in reality it represses a range of moments that are actually the unconscious foundation of its character.
One such repressed moment, indeed the foundational repression of capital in its pretense as a viable social relation, is the necessary codependence of $M$ and $C$ in the structure of its reasoning about value.
#footnote[In Volume III in particular, Marx details at length the grave consequences of treating $M$ as an independent entity that autonomously valorizes itself to $M'$, rather than recognizing that $'$ as a surplus-value that is always produced through its movement through $C$ as an intermediary value, as a dependent rather than independent variable.
  See @bestAutomaticFetishLaw2024 for an excellent exposition of these consequences.]

